featured_reviews.review_id:
la taquwmu lsWa`a@u HatWa~ yatabaha~ lnWasu fiy lmasajidi>>

(The Hour will not come until people show off in building Masjids.) It was recorded by Ahmad and the compilers of the Sunan, with the exception of At-Tirmidhi.Buraydah narrated that a man called out in the Masjid and said, "Has any body said anything about a red camel'' The Prophet said:

<<la, wajadta, inWama buniyati lmasajidu lima buniyat lahu>>

(May you never find it! The Masjids were built only for what they were built for.) This was narrated by Muslim. Abu Hurayrah, may Allah be pleased with him, narrated that the Messenger of Allah said:

<<idha ra'aytum man yabiy`u 'aw yabta`u fiy lmasjidi, faquwluw: la 'arbaHa llhu tijarataka, waidha ra'aytum man yanshudu DalWa@an fiy lmasjidi faquwluw: la radWaha llhu `alayka>>

(If you see someone buying or selling in the Masjid, say to him, "May Allah never make your business profitable!'' And if you see someone calling out about lost property, say, "May Allah never return it to you!'') This was recorded by At-Tirmidhi, who said: "Hasan Gharib.'' Al-Bukhari recorded that As-Sa'ib bin Yazid Al-Kindi said, "I was standing in the Masjid and a man threw pebbles at me, so I looked and saw `Umar bin Al-Khattab who said, `Go and bring me these two men.' I went and brought them to him, and he said, `Who are you' Or, `Where do you come from' They said, `We are from At-Ta'if.' `Umar said, `If you had been from this town I would have hit you, for you are raising your voices in the Masjid of the Messenger of Allah .''' An-Nasa'i recorded that Ibrahim bin `Abdur-Rahman bin `Awf said: "`Umar heard the voice of a man in the Masjid and said: `Do you know where you are''' This is also Sahih. Al-Hafiz Abu Ya`la Al-Musili recorded from Ibn `Umar that `Umar used to burn incense in the Masjid of the Messenger of Allah every Friday. Its chain of narration is Hasan and there is nothing wrong with it, Allah knows best.

featured_reviews.review_id:
The rowja sharif is situated at near by Silchar. The name of place is Mazumder bazar. The name of pir sahab is Idris Ali and his brother. There is two rowja. Dewar means fence, poles. The pir sahab abide by under the boundary fence. They are respecting curtain system that is parda. During his period, the followers are requested to the pir saheb that sufficient banana leaf is required. The banana leaf is used for distribution of the shinni at that time. The banana leaf is used as plate for fooding at the large number of people. At that time there is no tent house. They want to do banana planting. The pir sahab benedictions that we have no need fruits and corm only leaf is required. "The banana tree will give only leaf", blessing by the sahab. The banana tree following his blessings. The banana tree has not given banana or corm. The pir sahab's benediction is true still today.
There is a sufi Hermitage. Where the pir sahab performing ebadat. This is very sacred.
The people are come here various parts of the Barak Valley. They're doing shinni, jiarot dua and other ebadot. Every Thursday after Magrib performing khothme khajegan, shinni and dua etc.

featured_reviews.review_id:
la taquwmu lsWa`a@u HatWa~ yatabaha~ lnWasu fiy lmasajidi>>

(The Hour will not come until people show off in building Masjids.) It was recorded by Ahmad and the compilers of the Sunan, with the exception of At-Tirmidhi.Buraydah narrated that a man called out in the Masjid and said, "Has any body said anything about a red camel'' The Prophet said:

<<la, wajadta, inWama buniyati lmasajidu lima buniyat lahu>>

(May you never find it! The Masjids were built only for what they were built for.) This was narrated by Muslim. Abu Hurayrah, may Allah be pleased with him, narrated that the Messenger of Allah said:

<<idha ra'aytum man yabiy`u 'aw yabta`u fiy lmasjidi, faquwluw: la 'arbaHa llhu tijarataka, waidha ra'aytum man yanshudu DalWa@an fiy lmasjidi faquwluw: la radWaha llhu `alayka>>

(If you see someone buying or selling in the Masjid, say to him, "May Allah never make your business profitable!'' And if you see someone calling out about lost property, say, "May Allah never return it to you!'') This was recorded by At-Tirmidhi, who said: "Hasan Gharib.'' Al-Bukhari recorded that As-Sa'ib bin Yazid Al-Kindi said, "I was standing in the Masjid and a man threw pebbles at me, so I looked and saw `Umar bin Al-Khattab who said, `Go and bring me these two men.' I went and brought them to him, and he said, `Who are you' Or, `Where do you come from' They said, `We are from At-Ta'if.' `Umar said, `If you had been from this town I would have hit you, for you are raising your voices in the Masjid of the Messenger of Allah .''' An-Nasa'i recorded that Ibrahim bin `Abdur-Rahman bin `Awf said: "`Umar heard the voice of a man in the Masjid and said: `Do you know where you are''' This is also Sahih. Al-Hafiz Abu Ya`la Al-Musili recorded from Ibn `Umar that `Umar used to burn incense in the Masjid of the Messenger of Allah every Friday. Its chain of narration is Hasan and there is nothing wrong with it, Allah knows best.

featured_reviews.review_id:
la taquwmu lsWa`a@u HatWa~ yatabaha~ lnWasu fiy lmasajidi>>

(The Hour will not come until people show off in building Masjids.) It was recorded by Ahmad and the compilers of the Sunan, with the exception of At-Tirmidhi.Buraydah narrated that a man called out in the Masjid and said, "Has any body said anything about a red camel'' The Prophet said:

<<la, wajadta, inWama buniyati lmasajidu lima buniyat lahu>>

(May you never find it! The Masjids were built only for what they were built for.) This was narrated by Muslim. Abu Hurayrah, may Allah be pleased with him, narrated that the Messenger of Allah said:

<<idha ra'aytum man yabiy`u 'aw yabta`u fiy lmasjidi, faquwluw: la 'arbaHa llhu tijarataka, waidha ra'aytum man yanshudu DalWa@an fiy lmasjidi faquwluw: la radWaha llhu `alayka>>

(If you see someone buying or selling in the Masjid, say to him, "May Allah never make your business profitable!'' And if you see someone calling out about lost property, say, "May Allah never return it to you!'') This was recorded by At-Tirmidhi, who said: "Hasan Gharib.'' Al-Bukhari recorded that As-Sa'ib bin Yazid Al-Kindi said, "I was standing in the Masjid and a man threw pebbles at me, so I looked and saw `Umar bin Al-Khattab who said, `Go and bring me these two men.' I went and brought them to him, and he said, `Who are you' Or, `Where do you come from' They said, `We are from At-Ta'if.' `Umar said, `If you had been from this town I would have hit you, for you are raising your voices in the Masjid of the Messenger of Allah .''' An-Nasa'i recorded that Ibrahim bin `Abdur-Rahman bin `Awf said: "`Umar heard the voice of a man in the Masjid and said: `Do you know where you are''' This is also Sahih. Al-Hafiz Abu Ya`la Al-Musili recorded from Ibn `Umar that `Umar used to burn incense in the Masjid of the Messenger of Allah every Friday. Its chain of narration is Hasan and there is nothing wrong with it, Allah knows best.
